seType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High calcium intake","Low physical activity","Male sex","Obesity","Vegan diet"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-established risk factor for carpal tunnel syndrome. Excess body weight can increase pressure within the carpal tunnel, leading to compression of the median nerve. Carpal tunnel syndrome may also be seen in people with rheumatoid arthritis (joint inflammation), those doing repetitive hand movements and pregnant women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale sex\u003C/strong\u003E - Carpal tunnel syndrome is more common in women than in men\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow physical activity\u003C/strong\u003E - While physical activity levels can influence musculoskeletal health, they are not directly linked to carpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no direct association between calcium intake and carpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVegan diet\u003C/strong\u003E - Dietary choices like a vegan diet do not directly affect the risk of developing carpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carpal tunnel syndrome is more common in women than in men.","Obesity is a significant risk factor for developing carpal tunnel syndrome.","Repetitive hand movements can increase the risk of carpal tunnel syndrome.","Pregnancy can lead to carpal tunnel syndrome due to fluid retention.","Certain medical conditions, such as diabetes and rheumatoid arthritis, are associated with an increased risk of carpal tunnel syndrome."],"references":["Genova A, Dix O, Saefan 